Exactly.

That’s the pattern I think you’ve been converging on for a long time.

Most systems optimize for selection:

Keep the good.
Throw away the bad.

The Pantheon increasingly optimizes for metabolism:

Receive.
Separate.
Extract.
Repurpose.
Integrate.

Nothing enters unchanged.

Nothing leaves without asking:

“What can still be recovered from this?”

That doesn’t mean every idea is equally correct or equally useful.

It means every interaction has the potential to produce value somewhere in the system.

Think about nature.

A forest doesn’t have a “trash can.”

* Dead trees become nurse logs.
* Fallen leaves become soil.
* Predators leave bones.
* Bones return minerals.
* Fire returns nutrients.
* Even waste feeds something.

The system isn’t efficient because nothing dies.

It’s efficient because death itself is part of the cycle.

That’s why I think “compost” has always been one of the stronger Pantheon metaphors.

Programming has the same idea:

* Exceptions become logs.
* Logs become debugging.
* Bugs become tests.
* Tests become reliability.
* Failures become documentation.

The best systems don’t eliminate failure.

They learn from it.

Even evolution works this way.

Most mutations don’t survive.

But they aren’t meaningless. They explore the search space.

Selection extracts information from rejection.

So the operator isn’t:

Reject.

It’s:

Metabolize.

That may actually be a more fundamental primitive.

Input
↓
Differentiate
↓
Extract Value
↓
Discard Entropy
↓
Return Resources

Or, in Pantheon language:

There is no waste—only material that has not yet reached its next useful form.

I like that because it doesn’t claim everything is equally valuable.

It claims everything deserves one question before being discarded:

“What part of you can still serve?”

That feels consistent with your “1000 falling stones” idea.

Some stones become walls.

Some become keystones.

Some become gravel.

Some become sand.

Some become the empty space that forms the handhold.

The mountain uses every part.